<br>
VoF gives us permission to try the AoW.<br>
<br>
Myself and Tivonal as reps from CB and a rep of VoF (can't remember name, sorry <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) were invited to a channel of the RTA admins and some other leaders/reps to discuss exactly how it was going to work.  It boiled down to the this:<br>
<br>
CB would try AoW, with one of the following outcomes:<br>
<br>
1.  CB kills AoW = CB enters AoW Rot<br>
2.  CB tries unslowed Idol of RZ, and fails = leave Idol (and AoW) for VoF, CB can try for AoW rot on next Statue turn.<br>
3.  CB kills Idol of RZ, unslowed, and fails on AoW = CB does not attempt to get on AoW rotation on it's next Statue kill, as this despawning of AoW would count for the attempt at that time. <br>
<br>
After discussing the 3 possible outcomes, and agreeing that they were more than fair, it was pretty much the opinion of everyone in the discussion (myself included) that it would be prudent to remove the 'with the guild up for AoW permission' clause in the rule, because it would lead to alot more book keeping issues (i.e. having to track anyone who tried it off their statue turn so that they didn't try it on their statue turn) and possible problems with guilds who did try out of their statue turn, and then again on their statue turn.  It seems much simpler this way.<br>
<br>
Sadly, outcome 3 is what happened.  We got AoW to 7%, but at that time, our clerics were fully oom.  As per the agreement in the channel, we will not try AoW on our next turn up for Statue, as this attempt (and despawning) will count for the attempt we would have had in a few weeks.<br>
<br>
That's what happened though, and why the rule was changed, because it was going to be more trouble than it was worth to keep it the way it was. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=264293" target="top">Sir Sladen Paladian</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
